{"batchcomplete":"","query":{"normalized":[{"from":"saifi","to":"Saifi"}],"pages":{"23985201":{"pageid":23985201,"ns":0,"title":"Saifi","revisions":[{"contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox caste\n|caste_name= Saifi\n|classification= [[Muslim]], [[artisans]]\n|subdivisions= none\n|related castes ='''[[Sayyid]]'''  \n|populated_states=[[Uttar Pradesh]] [[India]] and [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] [[Pakistan]]\n|languages=[[Hindi language|Hindi]] and [[Urdu language|Urdu]]\n|religions=[[Islam]]}}\n\nThe Saifi are a [[Muslim]] community found primarily in the [[Uttar Pradesh]] state in India. They are also known as Muslim [[Lohar]].<ref>People of India Uttar Pradesh Volume XLII Part Three by K S Singh page 1240 Manohar Publications</ref>\n\nOther Saifi communities exist in Pakistan, Sri Lanka, and Nepal. Many of these follow orders of [[Sufism]] from the influence of [[Akhundzada Saif-ur-Rahman Mubarak]].\n\n== History & Origin ==\n\nThe Saifi are a community associated with the occupation of carpentry and ironsmithy. Their name comes from the [[Arabic]] word Saif, which means a sword. Like many other artisan communities in [[North India]], they claim descent from [[Arab]] immigrants to [[India]], who arrived during the period of the [[Delhi Sultanate]] <ref>People of India Uttar Pradesh Volume XLII Part Three by K S Singh page 1240 Manohar Publications</ref>\n\nThey speak [[Urdu]], as well as local dialect's of [[Hindi]].\n\n== Present Circumstances ==\n\nThe Saifi are a [[Sunni]] [[Muslim]] community. They also visit the shrines of various [[Sufi]] saints found in [[North India]], such as Khwaja [[Moinuddin Chishti]].<ref>People of India Uttar Pradesh Volume XLII Part Three by K S Singh page 1240 Manohar Publications</ref>\n\nThey are a landless community, involved with wood carving and wood engravings. Many have also taking to the modern occupation of being mechanics, and selling furniture, sawmills and workshops with lathe machines for the manufacture of spare parts.They are now considered as forming a community with in the [[Shaikh (caste)|Shaikh]] caste.<ref>People of India Uttar Pradesh Volume XLII Part Three by K S Singh page 1243 Manohar Publications</ref>\n\nThe Saifi have their own council of elders to deal with matters relating to the community. This panchayat deals with issues such as elopment, fights, thefts and disrespect of community norms. They are an endogamous community, and cross cousin and parrelel cousin marriages are prevalent.\nthe name saifi community is given by molana farqualeet sahab.\n\n== Distribution ==\n\nIn [[Uttar Pradesh]], they are primarily found in the [[SAHARANPUR]], [[MORADABAD]], [[Bulandshahr]], [[Bijnor]], [[Muzaffarnagar]], [[Meerut]] and [[Aligarh]] districts, with other significant populations existing in [[Lucknow]], [[Bareilly]], and [[Gorakhpur]].. They are also present in the [[Rohilkhand]] region, as well as in [[Delhi]].<ref>People of India Uttar Pradesh Volume XLII Part Three by K S Singh page 1240 Manohar Publications</ref>\n\nQuite a few Saifi have immigrated to [[Pakistan]], where they form an important element in the [[Muhajir (Pakistan)|Muhajir]] community.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Shaikhs in South Asia]]\n* [[Hajjam]]\n* [[Qassab]]\n* [[Momin Ansari]]\n* [[Manihar]]\n* [[Muslim Halwai]]\n* [[Kasgar]]\n* [[Bhatiara]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Muslim communities of India]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Social groups of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Shaikh clans]]\n[[Category:Muhajir communities]]"}]}}}}